{
  "texts": [
    "What does an AMR Capture?Over time, AMR conventions and standards have been changed to include more linguistic phenomena and increase their application for downstream tasks.",
    "Despite these changes, AMR in its foundational format captures a wide variety of semantic and syntactic features, including:• Frame Arguments: AMR uses PropBank framesets to represent the semantic roles of words in a sentence.",
    "For example, the frameset \"desire-01\" has slots for the wanter (:arg0), the wanted (:arg1).",
    "• General Semantic Relations: In addition to frame arguments, AMR uses nearly 100 general semantic relations to capture relationships between entities, events, and properties.",
    "This includes semantic relations such as time, location, and manner.• Coreference: AMR represents coreference by reusing variables to refer to the same entity."
  ]
}